 <div class="title" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">2.5. Avoided Impacts</div>
 <p xmlns="http://www.w3.org/1999/xhtml">The impacts of extreme high-temperature events that are avoided by a lower warming level (e.g., 2.0 °C or 1.5 °C) compared with the INDC scenario were investigated using the following equation:
  <div id="FD2-ijerph-16-02661" class="disp-formula">
   <span class="label">(2)</span>
   <div id="mm9" class="math">
    <div class="mrow">
     <div class="mrow">
      <div class="mrow">
       <span class="mi">Avoid</span>
       <span class="mtext"> </span>
       <span class="mi">Imapct</span>
      </div>
      <span class="mo">=</span>
      <div class="mfrac">
       <div class="mrow">
        <div class="msub">
         <span class="mi">C</span>
         <div class="mrow">
          <span class="mi">I</span>
          <span class="mi">N</span>
          <span class="mi">D</span>
          <span class="mi">C</span>
         </div>
        </div>
        <span class="mo">−</span>
        <div class="msub">
         <span class="mi">C</span>
         <span class="mi">k</span>
        </div>
       </div>
       <div class="mrow">
        <div class="msub">
         <span class="mi">C</span>
         <div class="mrow">
          <span class="mi">I</span>
          <span class="mi">N</span>
          <span class="mi">D</span>
          <span class="mi">C</span>
         </div>
        </div>
       </div>
      </div>
      <span class="mo">,</span>
     </div>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div> where 
  <div class="inline-formula">
   <div id="mm10" class="math">
    <div class="mrow">
     <span class="mi">C</span>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div> represents the changes in extreme high-temperature indices under a specific scenario compared with the present climatology, and the subscript 
  <div class="inline-formula">
   <div id="mm11" class="math">
    <div class="mrow">
     <span class="mi">k</span>
    </div>
   </div>
  </div> indicates different scenarios (e.g., 2.0 °C/1.5 °C). Such information is beneficial for future mitigation and adaptation planning.
 </p>
